  <p class="about_p">After installing AntConc, choose “Open File" or “Open Dir" (to open a directory containing multiple text files) from the File menu to begin analyzing your text files.  Files must be in a .txt format, with UTF-8 formatting.  If your file is in a different format, the creator of AntConc also offers file converter and encoding software, which can be <a href="http://www.laurenceanthony.net/software.html">downloaded for free from this website</a>.  Initially, AntConc would crash when I tried to load my WestHollywood all-text file, despite seeming to have the proper encoding; after running it through EncodeAnt, I was able to load it into AntConc without issue.  Therefore, if you have trouble loading a text file, it might be worth installing EncodeAnt.  Additionally, AntConc handles many smaller files much better than one large text file, so if you are having trouble with the program crashing while analyzing your source, <a href="https://stackoverflow.com/questions/2016894/how-to-split-a-large-text-file-into-smaller-files-with-equal-number-of-lines">you can split the file into multiple smaller files</a> and try running those through instead.</p>

